{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c2e0db7a-b362-4929-ab1a-d11793165440","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.0+ dropped the VSTest bridge by default.**\n\nIn 3.x, the SDK implicitly included `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.VSTestBridge`, so `vstest.console` could still discover and run tests. Starting with 4.0, only the new **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** runner is wired up out of the box — `vstest.console` sees no tests because the adapter is gone.\n\n### You have two options\n\n**Option 1 (recommended) — switch CI to `dotnet test`:**\n\n```\ndotnet test TestProject.csproj\n```\n\n`dotnet test` already uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform for MSTest.Sdk 4.x projects. No project changes needed.\n\n**Option 2 — re-enable the VSTest bridge:**\n\nAdd this property to your csproj:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <EnableVSTestBridge>true</EnableVSTestBridge>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis brings back the adapter so `vstest.console` can discover tests again, but Microsoft recommends migrating away from it long-term.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60356bf0-06e2-4c6e-843b-611ccb8edd0a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a known breaking change in MSTest.Sdk. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.x, the project uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the new test platform). In MSTest.Sdk/3.x, the VSTest bridge was included by default so that vstest.console could still discover and run tests. However, starting with MSTest.Sdk/4.0.0, the VSTest bridge adapter is no longer included by default. This means vstest.console can no longer discover tests unless you explicitly opt in.\n\nThe key change: **MSTest.Sdk 4.0+ no longer ships the VSTest bridge by default**. \n\nSo now tests only work with the new Microsoft.Testing.Platform—either through `dotnet test` or running the test executable directly. If you're still using vstest.console, you'll need to either migrate your CI pipeline to `dotnet test` (which is the recommended approach), or explicitly enable the VSTest adapter by setting a project property or adding the bridge package as a dependency. In MSTest.Sdk 3.x, the VSTest bridge was included by default so both `vstest.console` and the new `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` runner worked seamlessly. Starting with 4.0+, only the new runner is supported by default, which breaks compatibility with the older test runner.\n\nThe solution depends on the situation: I can either recommend migrating the CI pipeline to use `dotnet test` instead, which natively supports the new testing platform, or add a property to the project file to re-enable the VSTest bridge as a temporary workaround.","outputTokens":948,"requestId":"7035:32FCC3:483BD3:54A925:69F2C334"},"id":"1c2bbf5a-f873-418e-8bc8-ca5b3b54c403","timestamp":"2026-04-30T02:49:45.173Z","parentId":"8dc1e23a-eaec-4d1f-bc2c-f72734e638c3"}
